text: not a four. Short of a length outside off, Sehwag stays behind the line and punches into the covers
preText:
Right, not much of a break. The players are out there. Sehwag is ready, Sachin's with him. The fielders are in position. Can Sehwag hit a first-ball four again? India need a lot of those. Won't be easy against Malinga. This is Nitin Sundar to start off commentary for the chase.

Swamy: "India's strategy has now been inverted thanks to that brilliant knock from Mahela. What happens in the first 15 overs will now dictate whether India win. Anything less than 100+ for no loss or 1 wicket means its SL's game."

Mazher: "Mahela Jaywardene has never scored a century in losing cause, his all 13 centuries - before today - were match winning" Not sure if true, but if it is, that's a staggering stat ...

Calvin: "I certainly don't see India getting these runs ,to win the world cup.As we can see there is some bounce in the wicket, which plays right into the hands of the Sri lankan's, bowlers." Debatable, Calvin. As far as I know, Sri Lanka's bowlers prefer slow and low pitches, not ones with good carry and little turn (which is how it has been so far). Plus, this is a small outfield. But, in a World Cup final, 274 is a mountain.

Guru: "I know this is far-fetched, but think of it - Sachin getting his 100th 100 and winning the title for India, chasing a big total in a high-pressure final. How better can things get?" Well, so far this World Cup, India have managed to give their fans everything they wanted. This seems like the steepest demand of all, but who am I to bet against them pulling it off ...

Sivabhaskar: "I've already started getting nightmares of a rain of in-swinging-yorkers -- Malinga !" and "A wicked kind of a compensation. Zaheer leaked at death what he contained at the birth."

6:50pm IST Thanks Abhishek. Boy, that was some innings from Mahela! The innings of the World Cup, possibly challenged only by KOB's blitz against England. Gilchrist and Ponting played classics in 2007 and 2003 finals... how good was this in comparison?
currentInning.team.name: India

text: Given out lbw, and immediately reviewed. Looks like a goner on replay! Back of a length delivery on middle stump, Sehwag was rising on the toes on leg stump line as it skidded through. He was on the hop as he closed the face and looked to flick. Misses the shot. Was there an inside edge? No evidence of that. Was that high? Not really - hit him under the roll. It's hitting middle. Three reds. Superb start for Sri Lanka! Sehwag top-scored for India in the 2003 final. Fair to say, he won't be the top scorer today.

preText:
It'll be Bhuvneshwar Kumar to take the new ball. Can he light this contest up like Shaheen Afridi did in Dubai last year? Two slips in place. Here we go!

Rohit leads India's huddle on the outfield. Babar and Rizwan wait pitch-side. Pakistan have been a brilliant chasing team over the last two years but can they post a defendable total after being inserted?

6.55pm: The MCG is rammed. Flags waving in every stand, not a spare seat in the house. The players walk out through the tunnel, and line up for the anthems. Rohit Sharma looks almost overwhelmed by the noise as India's draws to an end.

Zak: "To break up the millions of Indian/Pakistani comments, as an Aussie, I just got goosebumps with the anthems just now. What a moment that was. Feels like the final all ready!"

Shahzad: "Will have to follow the game while "working" in the office. Alt Tab to the rescue." -- You won't be alone in that.

6.45pm: Thanks, KK. The build-up is nearly over, and the biggest game in cricket at the biggest stadium in Australia is only 15 minutes away. Let me know your thoughts on the teams: surprised that Yuzvendra Chahal has been left out?

Rajesh: "I would have thought this would be the ideal match for Pant. Disrupt the Shadab, Nawaz combination against a completely right hand top order"

Sabith: "This is not the biggest game. The biggest game will be India vs Pakistan final at the very same venue next month :p"

Datta: "Rohit Sharma found a Pep Guardiola. A very left field selection. Will haunt then back"

Adarsh: "Interesting that Shami couldn't find a place in the original squad, and was brought in as a replacement for Bumrah. And he finds a place in the starting XI ahead of Harshal Patel. This points to some inconsistencies in the selection process."

Alex Malcolm at the MCG: "It's very rare to have a T20 game at the MCG this early in the Australian summer. Normally there is only first-class cricket played here at this time of year. Last year this pitch had a lot of spice in it in November and December in red ball cricket, particularly when curator Matt Page left plenty of grass on it. Traditionally white ball pitches at the MCG don't have much grass for the BBL in January. This has a decent covering. It will be intriguing to see if there is swing, seam and bounce for India first up."

Gaurav Sundararaman points out that chasing has been the way to go in India-Pakistan T20Is. The team batting first has not won one since 2012; the chasing team has won the last six.

6.35pm Here are the teams.

Pakistan: 1 Mohammad Rizwan, 2 Babar Azam, 3 Shan Masood, 4 Shadab Khan, 5 Haider Ali, 6 Iftikhar Ahmed, 7 Mohammad Nawaz, 8 Asif Ali, 9 Shaheen Shah Afridi, 10 Naseem Shah, 11 Haris Rauf.

India 1 Rohit Sharma, 2 KL Rahul, 3 Virat Kohli, 4 Suryakumar Yadav, 5 Hardik Pandya, 6 Dinesh Karthik, 7 Axar Patel, 8 R Ashwin, 9 Mohammed Shami, 10 Bhuvneshwar Kumar, 11 Arshdeep Singh.

Interesting selection from India. Shami and Ashwin in, Harshal and Chahal out. The rest is along expected lines. Ashwin's selection suggests two things - India are aware of the possibility of Nawaz floating up the order, and are aiming to disrupt this. And they also know that Babar and Rizwan don't really attack offspin that much. And also, Ashwin isn't just an offspinner. Against right-handers, his stock balls come out of the front of the hand - the carrom ball and the reverse carrom ball, and his record against RHBs is top-notch.

Pakistan had a difficult choice to make, to pick three seamers out of the five superb ones they have. They've gone with Shaheeh Shah Afridi, Haris Rauf and Naseem Shah.

With those observations, I'll take a little break, and welcome Matt Roller into the commentary pod.

6.30pm Rohit tosses, Babar calls tails, and it's heads. India will bowl first.

"Looks like a good pitch, a bit of grass, and it's a little overcast, so the ball might swing around a little bit, so we'll try and use that to our advantage," Rohit says. "Very much sorted with our preparation now. It's time to come out and enjoy ourselves."

Team composition: "Seven batters, an allrounder, three seamers, two spinners." Rohit doesn't say who will fill those roles. And it adds up to 12.

Babar smartly takes the cue from Rohit. "Three fast bowlers, two spinners, and the rest are batsmen."

6.25pm Around 20 minutes ago (it's gotten a little cloudier since):

6.20pm What does the pitch look like? According to Michael Clarke, it's an "absolute beauty". A bit of green grass on top, and it's "rock hard". "A beautiful batting pitch once you get in, get past that new ball." He suggests that the captain winning the toss bat first. Interesting.

Jiten Chandaran: "It looks like Ashwin is playing, so that means they have some batting at 8, which allows Shami to come in for Harshal. I expect now."

Fiaz Laghari: "A while ago, we friends left our room to get some breakfast and everyone out here on the roads seems to be in a great rush. It's like a storm is coming and people are rushing to some safe place, that is how the excitement level is here in Lahore for Pak-Ind clash. Everyone trying to get their things done before the match starts."

6.15pm Virat Kohli's just given India's players an animated pep talk. We're also hearing that Mohammed Shami is marking out his run-up. If he plays, it'll be his 18th T20I. Half of them, Sampath Bandarupalli informs me, have come at World Cups. That's quite a stat.

Adarsh: "Here's a left-field opinion: India should have Pant open today to create a left-right combination against Shaheen Shah Afridi and hopefully mess with his lines."

BW: "Could this be the most viewed cricinfo commentary of all time? No pressure, Karthik."

6.05pm Monga is watching India train, and his observations tell him Rishabh Pant probably isn't playing tonight.

"Pakistan have put up three national flags on their warm-up side of the field," Monga adds. "India zero." Make of this what you will.

Syed: "Dreadful weather here in my town Swindon but terrific news about the weather in Melbourne hopefully to watch a full match without interference." -- I don't think this has any basis in science, but the more rain there is in every non-Melbourne city in the world, the less the chances of rain in Melbourne. Swindon is doing its bit for cricket!

Syed Habeeb: "What is the news about Fakhar Zaman?" -- He hasn't recovered fully from his knee issue, so he's not available today.

5.55pm Here are two fantastic pieces on two fantastic Pakistan players: Alex Malcolm chats with the former Melbourne Stars list manager Trent Woodhill about Haris Rauf, who'll come into tonight's game with plenty of local knowledge of the conditions. And Danyal Rasool interviews the ebullient and thoughtful Shadab Khan, Pakistan's Mr. T20.

If you're in the US, you can watch the game live on ESPN+.

If any of you collect player cards, autographed bats or other memorabilia from cricket games, you may be interested in their digital versions. This World Cup, the cricket world is meeting the world of digital collectibles. ESPNcricinfo's digital collectibles partners FanCraze are allowing fans to pre-buy iconic moments from each match of the World Cup called the Crictos of the Game. We'll also have a weekly video series here on ESPNcricinfo with our experts picking our favourite moments of the week.

For the fantasy players and gamers among you, you may want to check out a game from our digital collectibles partners Fan Craze - the FanCraze Flash Nets game, where you use digital collectibles to play and earn rewards.

Akhil: "This is probably first time after 2007 T20 WC that India are not coming into the match as favourites. Though we can't say Pakistan are expected to win, brace yourselves for an exciting match"

Saurabh: "I have three work colleagues from Pakistan here in Perth. We share and align almost on everything from food to thoughts, from wishing each other on Diwali and Eid. This is the day when we won't align as it is India vs Pak :P"

5.40pm In case you haven't noticed already, our Live Blog is up and running. And if it's expert opinions you're after, who better than Anil Kumble and Stephen Fleming to set things up?

Arun Heer: "Welcome to a clash which is not less than a festival in these two nations playing each other! We're more than 100 members of 'Langley Lions', a cricket team of local players in British Columbia, CANADA, all awake to to watch at 1 AM local time. God will change plans and postpone rain as he has to watch this clash too, agreed??"

Mustafa Moudi : "Last 4 results between these 2 sides in T20I (Oldest first) - India Won (T20 WC '16), Pakistan Won (T20 WC '21), India Won (Asia Cup '22 Group Stage) and Pakistan Won (Asia Cup '22 Super 4). Going by the pattern.... IYKWIM !!"

5.30pm Hello, hello. Welcome to ESPNcricinfo's coverage of the latest chapter in the friendliest, most bonhomious (it's officially a word now) rivalry in all cricket. You'll be pleased to know that Melbourne is bathed in bright sunlight at the moment, judging by the images our correspondent Sidharth Monga is sending over. Fans in blue and green are streaming into the 'G as we speak, having squeezed out of the traffic jam encircling the stadium. We're an hour away from the toss, and we really cannot wait.

Siddharth: "It's time for the greatest sporting event of the year. Can't wait!!"

Hamza: "Hello everyone from Pakistan! Was waiting impatiently for this telecast to get started. Usual stuff, sleepless night. Surely, a contest bewteen quality bowling and batting today. I think India have an edge, they have got quality batting with depth and consistency. Pakistani batters are not reliabale apart from openers. On such difficult batting tracks you need good technic like Indian batsmen. Good luck to both teams."

shortText: Arshdeep Singh to Babar Azam, OUT
text: full, straight, pinned lbw first ball! Erasmus raises the finger but Babar will review. This looked stone dead live. Full, swinging into the pads. Babar was looking to work it away with a roll of the wrists but it skidded into his shin. Was it doing too much to clip leg stump? Ultra-Edge confirms no bat involved. Pitched in line, impact in line, hitting leg stump three-quarters of the way up! Babar trudges off.
preText: Arshdeep will share the new ball. One slip, over the wicket. "Babar, Babar!" is the chant.
postText:
Alex Malcolm at the MCG: "I was at the MCG when Shane Warne took his 700th Test wicket. The roar when Marais Erasmus just raised his finger was louder than that."

Wow. What a huge moment for Arshdeep Singh and for India! The captain goes first-ball and Arshdeep strikes on the biggest stage.
